# AIPlane — Best Practices

## Commits and PRs
- Match the PR template's "Type of change" categories (bug fix / feature / breaking /
  docs / chore) in your commit and PR title — prefixes like `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`,
  `docs:`, `test:`, `ci:` keep history scannable (see the sub-issue titles created from
  the repo audit for the convention already in use).
- Every PR links an issue (`Closes #N`) per `CONTRIBUTING.md` — don't open a PR without a
  tracked issue behind it, even for small fixes.
- Keep commits focused; don't bundle an unrelated refactor into a feature PR.

## Docs stay in sync with code
- `docs/SPEC.md` and `docs/ISSUE_WORKFLOW.md` are the source of truth for architecture and
  roadmap status. If a PR changes scope, adds a phase, or splits an issue, update these
  docs **in the same PR** — not as a follow-up. A stale roadmap doc is worse than no doc.
- When an issue is split into sub-issues (as happened for #14-#17), comment on the parent
  with the sub-issue numbers and update `docs/ISSUE_WORKFLOW.md`'s tracker table to match —
  don't leave the parent issue's body as the only source of truth.

## Error handling and resilience
- Each Module Federation remote gets its own Suspense boundary + error boundary in the
  dashboard host (see `.cursor/rules/module-federation.mdc`) — a broken remote must not
  take down the whole shell.
- Prefer explicit, typed error states in `packages/api-client` hooks (loading/error/success)
  over throwing raw fetch errors up to components.

## Accessibility
- `packages/ui` is built on shadcn/ui, which is accessible by default (proper roles, focus
  management, keyboard nav) — don't strip `aria-*` attributes or replace semantic elements
  (`<button>`, `<label>`) with unstyled `<div>`s for convenience.
- New interactive components (guardrail rule builder, user manager forms, etc.) should be
  operable by keyboard alone — this is also what makes them testable via RTL's
  `getByRole`/`getByLabelText` queries.

## Backend conventions
- Spring Actuator + Micrometer are the observability layer — use structured logging
  (SLF4J) with meaningful log levels; don't `System.out.println` or log at `INFO` for
  high-frequency request-level detail.
- Keep the modular-monolith boundaries in `api-server` clean — domain packages
  (prompts, guardrails, users, usage) shouldn't reach into each other's internals directly;
  go through service interfaces.

## Repo hygiene
- Once `CODEOWNERS` and `CHANGELOG.md` exist (see the OSS-hygiene issues), respect them:
  add a CHANGELOG entry for user-facing changes in the same PR, and expect/request the
  relevant code owner's review rather than routing around it.
- Don't add ESLint, Prettier, Jest, or npm/yarn lockfiles — this repo has standardized on
  Biome, Vitest, and pnpm; introducing a second tool in the same role creates config drift.
